These relationships are used directly for back-calculating PRE values from known structures (and for refining against PRE data) as described below. The PRE measured for a given nucleus has a population-weighted ‚å©r‚àí6‚å™ dependence on the distance between the nucleus and the paramagnetic center, hence its utility as a structural restraint (and as a probe of minor states) emerges. However, because most paramagnetic tags used for measuring PRE are highly flexible (and the molecules of interest are also often quite flexible), it is important in structure calculations to refine directly against the PRE data (e.g. using prePot in XplorNIH (Iwahara et al. 2004b) as discussed below) rather than converting PRE data into a single distance, which is generally incorrect (although PRE calculators have been made available online at spin.niddk.nih.gov/clore for qualitative purposes).
Both the transverse and longitudinal PREs are infiuenced by internal motion (Iwahara et al. 2004b). However, while Œì1 has a complicated dependence on the internal correlation time, the Œì2 shows a simpler dependence. As the internal correlation time is increased from 0 (infinitely fast internal motion) to a value greater than the overall rotational correlation time, the ratio Œì2,SBMF/Œì2,SB (where Œì2,SBMF is Œì2 calculated from the SBMF equation, and Œì2,SB is Œì2 calculated from the SB equation) increases from the value of the order parameter (0 ‚â§
Q Rev Biophys. Author manuscript; available in PMC 2018 December 03.

Author Manuscript

Author Manuscript

Author Manuscript

Anthis and Clore

Page 31
S2 ‚â§ 1) to 1. For the longitudinal PRE, however, Œì1,SBMF/Œì1,SB first increases from the value of S2 when œÑi = 0, up to a maximum value ‚â´ 1 when œÑi ‚âà 1/œâ (where œâ is the resonance frequency of the observed nucleus in rad s‚àí1), before eventually approaching 1 (Iwahara et al. 2004b). Thus, whereas a simple estimation of œÑi is sufficient for structural analysis of 1H‚Äì Œì2 data, such treatment of 1H‚ÄìŒì1 data requires accurate information on œÑi for individual PRE vectors (Iwahara & Clore, 2010). Another complication is that, due to cross-relaxation and water exchange, 1H R1 relaxation does not follow a single-exponential curve. Thus, it is advantageous to measure the transverse PRE instead of the longitudinal PRE. For very fast motion (œÑi ‚â™ œÑr; i.e. picosecond timescale motion), the transverse PRE is virtually independent of the internal correlation time, and the order parameter acts as a scaling factor.
In either case, though, the SBMF equations reduce to the SB equations under conditions where the internal motion is either very slow (œÑt ‚âà œÑc) or highly restricted in space (S2 ‚âà 1).

3.1.2 PRE from minor states‚ÄîIn a system undergoing exchange between states on a fast timescale, the overall PRE profile observed for the ensemble of states is the populationweighted average of all the members of the ensemble. Owing to the ‚å©r‚àí6‚å™ distance dependence of the PRE, such a profile will be dominated by the states in which the paramagnetic center more closely approaches the observed nuclei. Thus, even if a state occupies a small (<10%) portion of the total population, it can be readily detected if it involves a shorter distance between a paramagnetic probe and reporter than the other state(s) (Fig. 2). Thus, an otherwise invisible minor state can be detected and structurally characterized using PRE (Clore & Iwahara, 2009).

Under fast exchange conditions on the PRE timescale (i.e. the rate of exchange between the species is much greater than the difference in PRE rates between states) the overall PRE observed for a nucleus is given by:

Œì2app = pi Œì2, i, (55)

Where Œì2app is the apparent transverse PRE measured for the entire ensemble Œì2,i PRE for state i, and pi is the population of state i. Eq. (55) holds when the rate of exchange is slower than the overall correlation time ( ex ‚â™ 1/œÑc); in the limit of ultrafast exchange, however, where ex ‚â´ 1/œÑc, in Eq. (55) would be replaced by Œì2app = pi Œì2, i 2 (i.e. under ultrafast exchange conditions the contribution of each state to Œì2app is roughly proportional to the square of its population due to the fact that individual components of Œì2app are averaged as <r ‚àí3> as opposed to <r‚àí6> under the more usual conditions of Eq. (55)). In the case of twostate exchange between a major state (A) and a minor state (B), the apparent observed PRE is given by:
Œì2app = pA Œì2, A + pB Œì2, B . (56)

