The rate constant Ì†µÌ≥Äoapnp is a pseudo-first-order rate constant because although it describes a reaction that is first-order with respect to A, the actual reaction could be of higher order.
In such an exchanging system, the observed transverse relaxation rate R2obs of state A can be enhanced by broadening due to differences in chemical shift between states A and B (Rex) and by broadening due to differences in transverse relaxation rate between the two states (lifetime line broadening, Rllb). Overall, the enhancement Œî R2obs to the transverse relaxation rate of state A is given by

R2obs = R20, A + Œî R2obs, (78)

where R20, A is the intrinsic relaxation of state A in the absence of exchange. The relative contributions of Rex and Rllb to Œî R2obs depend on the exchange rate and on the magnitude of chemical shift difference (Œîœâ = |œâA ‚àí œâB|) and transverse relaxation rate difference
Œî R20 = R20, B ‚àí R20, A between the states (Fig. 5).
If the rate of transverse relaxation in state B (the ‚Äòdark‚Äô state; R20, B = R2dark) is very rapid (due a large size and therefore slow tumbling), then any transverse magnetization that is transferred from A to B will effectively be destroyed. If the exchange is slow on the transverse relaxation timescale Ì†µÌ≥Äex ‚â™ Œî R20 , lifetime line broadening will be equal to the apparent first-order rate constant. Rllb = Ì†µÌ≥Äoapnp If, however, exchange is fast on the transverse relaxation timescale Ì†µÌ≥Äex ‚â´ Œî R20 , Œî R2obs will be a population-weighted average of the two relaxation rates:
R2obs = pAR20, A + pBR20, B (79)
(providing ex ‚â™ 1/œÑr, where œÑr is the rotational correlation time) and Rllb is given by:
Rllb = R2obs ‚àí R20, A = pB Œî R20 . (80)

For cases where the dark state B is very large and has a very rapid rate of transverse
relaxation (e.g. large macromolecular assemblies and aggregated species), lifetime line
broadening can only be measured in the slow exchange regime, unless pB is very small, because as R2obs approaches values of ‚àº100 s‚àí1 or larger, it becomes difficult or impossible to measure. For smaller assemblies with more moderate R20, B, lifetime line broadening can be measured in the intermediate and fast exchange regimes as well.

