Fig. 2. Characterizing a sparsely populated state by PRE. If a major state (A) is in exchange with a minor state (B), the effect of the minor state can be amplified by PRE if two points (corresponding to the paramagnetic center and observed nucleus) are in closer proximity in the minor state than in the major state. (a) In this example, the protein is in exchange
between an extended state (A, r = 40 √Ö) and a compact state (B, r = 8 √Ö). If a nitroxide spin label is attached to one point, the PRE measured for a proton at the other point would be virtually zero in state A (Œì2,A = 0¬∑12 s‚àí1), but very large in state B (Œì2,B = 1900 s‚àí1) causing broadening of the observed NMR signal. PRE values were calculated assuming a correlation
