time of œÑc = 10 ns (corresponding to a protein at room temperature with a molecular weight of ‚àº20 kDa). Spectra were calculated by solving the McConnell equations (Eqs. (16)‚Äì(20) and (57)) in MATLAB, assuming R2,dia = 10 s‚àí1 in each state (the height of the spectrum for state B [green] has been magnified 107 times for the purposes of visualization). If states A and B are in fast exchange on the PRE timescale (in this example: ex ‚â´ Œì2,A - Œì2,B = 1900 s‚àí1; œÑex ‚â™ 500 Œºs), the apparent PRE will be the population-averaged PRE of the two states
Œì2app = 0.99 √ó 0.12 s‚àí1 + 0.01 √ó 1900 s‚àí1 = 19.12 s‚àí1 Thus, even although state B comprises only 1% of the total population, Œì2app arises almost exclusively from this minor state. (b) If the exchange rate is slower, the apparent PRE measured for A will be less than the
population-weighted averaged PRE. Shown in black are simulated spectra for the system undergoing exchange with a rate of ex = 102, 103, or 104 s‚àí1. The dashed blue spectrum corresponds to the paramagnetic spectrum of A alone, and the dashed red spectrum
corresponds to the population-weighted averaged paramagnetic spectrum under very fast exchange conditions (106 s‚àí1). (c) Apparent PRE plotted against ex. The PRE increases from 0¬∑12 s‚àí1 for a system undergoing very slow exchange (the value for state A alone) to 19¬∑12 s‚àí1 for a system undergoing very fast exchange.

